        'Here\'s a design principle that sounds counterintuitive but becomes increasingly obvious once you understand the framework.',
        'Some of the best practice for high-performance situations looks absolutely nothing like those situations.',
        'Not because it\'s easier or simpler. Because it\'s been architecturally designed to isolate and develop a specific capacity at a level of intensity that the performance situation doesn\'t allow.',
        'A sprint coach might have a distance runner do exercises that look nothing like running — box jumps, single-leg balance drills, complex coordination sequences. From the outside, this looks irrelevant. From the inside of good practice design, it\'s targeting the specific neuromuscular capacities that break down in the final 200 meters of a race, in conditions that allow for a higher learning intensity than actual racing permits.',
        'A jazz educator might have a student play a single chord in every possible inversion across the entire range of the piano, slowly, for thirty minutes. This looks nothing like jazz performance — it has no rhythm, no phrase, no musical expression. But it\'s developing the harmonic differentiation that allows the improviser to make better choices in real time, at performance speed, under performance pressure.',
        'The connection between the practice and the performance is not in the surface structure. It\'s in the deep structure — the essential demands, the core perceptual requirements, the underlying capacities that performance requires.',
        'This is what Module 7 will go deeper on: representative learning design. But it\'s worth surfacing here because it affects how you think about constraint architecture in particular.',
        'When you design constraints, you\'re not trying to recreate performance conditions exactly. You\'re trying to recreate the essential demands of performance in conditions that allow for a higher developmental intensity. More failures per unit time. Tighter feedback. More deliberate targeting of the specific capacity.',
        'The constraint that makes this work is the one that preserves the essential demand while removing the noise. The noise is everything in the performance environment that doesn\'t actually matter for the capacity you\'re developing. The essential demand is the thing that matters.',
        'Strip the noise. Preserve the demand. Increase the intensity. That\'s the constraint architecture of practice that looks nothing like performance but produces experts who transfer beautifully into it.',
        'This principle has a corollary for feedback loop design: the metric you measure in practice doesn\'t have to be the same as the metric that matters in performance. You want the metric that most directly measures the capacity you\'re targeting. If you\'re developing decision speed, measure decision speed. If you\'re developing accuracy under fatigue, measure accuracy at specific fatigue levels. The performance metric is downstream. The practice metric is closer to the mechanism.',
        'Track what the practice is actually developing, not what you wish you were developing.',
