  theMove: 'Pick one skill you\'re actively developing. Before your next practice session, write out the full architecture for that session using the four variables. Be specific — not aspirational, not general. Specific.\n\nChallenge level: Where will you be working relative to your current capacity? What failure rate are you designing for? How will you know the challenge level is right?\n\nFeedback loop: What is the mechanism by which the environment will tell you whether you solved the problem? How quickly will you know? What does a good outcome look like versus a poor one — and is that distinction legible in real time?\n\nConstraint architecture: What are you making impossible in this session? What are you making necessary? What behavior do you want to emerge — and what is the constraint that makes that behavior the path of least resistance?\n\nRecovery structure: How will you reset after failure? What is the decision rule for when to stop and process versus when to continue? What is your micro-debrief protocol — the fifteen to thirty seconds between attempts where you extract the information from the failure before moving on?\n\nDo the session exactly as designed. Don\'t adjust the design mid-session based on how it feels — let the architecture run.\n\nAfterward: five minutes. Write down what the bowl actually demanded. What failures showed up? Were they the failures you designed for? What did you learn about where your capacity currently lives? What does that tell you about how to update the design for the next session?\n\nYou are not assessing your performance. You are updating your architecture. That is the debrief\'s only job.',
